  "prompt": "What are some ways to use Moga controllers on a PC?",
  "response": "MOGA controllers are primarily designed for mobile gaming but can also be used on a PC with some setup. Here are several ways to use a MOGA controller on a PC:\n\n### 1. **Via Bluetooth (For MOGA Pro or MOGA Hero Power)**\n   - **Step 1**: Ensure your PC has Bluetooth capability. If not, use a Bluetooth dongle.\n   - **Step 2**: Put your MOGA controller into pairing mode (usually by holding the MOGA button until it flashes).\n   - **Step 3**: On your PC, go to **Settings > Devices > Bluetooth & other devices** and pair the controller.\n   - **Step 4**: The controller should now be recognized as an input device. You can use it in games that support controllers or via software like XInput or DirectInput.\n\n### 2. **Via USB Cable**\n   - **Step 1**: Connect your MOGA controller to your PC using a compatible USB cable.\n   - **Step 2**: Windows should recognize the controller as a generic input device.\n   - **Step 3**: If not automatically recognized, you may need to install drivers or use third-party software like **XOutput** or **JoyToKey** to map the controller inputs to keyboard or mouse actions.\n\n### 3. **Using MOGA Universal Driver**\n   - MOGA provides a universal driver for Windows that allows the controller to function like an Xbox 360 controller.\n   - **Step 1**: Download and install the MOGA Universal Driver from the official website.\n   - **Step 2**: Connect your MOGA controller via USB or Bluetooth.\n   - **Step 3**: The driver will emulate the controller as an Xbox 360 controller, making it compatible with most PC games.\n\n### 4. **Using Third-Party Software**\n   - **XOutput**: This software can map MOGA controller inputs to Xbox 360 controller inputs, making it compatible with games that don\u2019t natively support MOGA.\n   - **JoyToKey**: This program allows you to map controller inputs to keyboard or mouse actions, enabling the use of a MOGA controller in games that don\u2019t support gamepads.\n   - **DS4Windows**: Although designed for PlayStation controllers, some versions of DS4Windows can emulate Xbox inputs for other controllers like MOGA.\n\n### 5. **Using Steam**\n   - Steam has built-in controller support for a wide range of gamepads.\n   - **Step 1**: Connect your MOGA controller to your PC.\n   - **Step 2**: Open Steam and go to **Settings > Controller > General Controller Settings**.\n   - **Step 3**: Enable the configuration support and follow the prompts to set up your MOGA controller.\n\n### 6. **Using Emulators**\n   - If you\u2019re using emulators to play retro games, many of them have built-in controller support. You can configure the MOGA controller within the emulator\u2019s input settings.\n\n### Tips:\n- Check the MOGA controller model for compatibility, as older models may have limited functionality on PC.\n- Be aware that some MOGA controllers may only work in \"HID mode\" when used wirelessly, which limits functionality compared to a wired connection.\n\nWith these methods, you should be able to use your MOGA controller effectively on a PC for a variety of games and applications.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
